.props` parser and utilizes map, system, and environment property sources, but doesn't involve services or Docker. I should note the documentation's mention that format-specific modules for YAML, JSON, TOML, and HOCON are needed if the agent wants to cover those. However, using static environment variables should be avoided if possible, especially when ensuring a single JSON object without markdown.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"no_action\",\n  \"summary\": \"No extra setup is concretely required for meaningful hoplite-core coverage: the resolved artifact only depends on Kotlin stdlib/reflect and kotlinx-coroutines, includes the built-in Java properties parser, and exposes core APIs that can be exercised with MapPropertySource, SystemPropertiesPropertySource, ConfigLoaderBuilder, decoders, preprocessors, and classpath/file sources without Docker or additional Maven modules.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"Hoplite documentation says YAML, JSON, TOML, and HOCON file parsing require separate hoplite format modules; generated tests should not rely on those formats unless such a module is intentionally added.\",\n    \"Hoplite 3.0 changes environment-variable mapping semantics, so tests that exercise environment variables may be sensitive to process environment setup; MapPropertySource or SystemPropertiesPropertySource are safer for deterministic core coverage.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_047732d3242e1a56016a4112acc71881939026d0c6036e41d2\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 900, "output": 711, "cacheRead": 31232, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 32843, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1782649504124, "responseId": "resp_047732d3242e1a56016a4112a097c48193b1b50bea86838da4"}, "toolResults": []}
